        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC">          
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-across"/><persName nymRef="#dovaidū"><name>ᚇᚑᚃᚐᚔᚇᚑᚅᚐ</name> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">ᚋᚐ ᚊᚔ</w> <name nymRef="#?">ᚇᚏᚑᚐᚈᚐ</name></persName>
                </ab> 
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-across"/><persName nymRef="#dovaidū"><name>DOVAIDONA</name> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">MA QI</w> <name nymRef="#?">DROATA</name></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
<note>Another possible reading:</note>  
                    <rdg>
                        <lb/>DOVAIDONA MA QI DRUTA <!--check with Megan!!-->
                    </rdg>
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>'[the memorial stone] of Dubáed, son of Droata' (Broderick 2021, 9).  </p>
                <p>Kermode (1910, 437) provides the following translation: '(the stone) of Dovaidu, son of the Druid'.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>Kermode (1907) takes <foreign xml:lang="sga">droata</foreign> as a variant of <foreign xml:lang="sga">druada</foreign> 'druid', but later authorities read <persName xml:lang="sga">Droata</persName> as a personal name. The first element of the first name DOV- may be influenced by Old Irish word <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/18985">dub</ref></foreign> meaning 'black'. The second element of the first personal name -AIDONA may be Old Irish <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/613">Áed</ref></foreign>, meaning 'fiery' with the individualising suffix *-<foreign xml:lang="sga">ón</foreign>. The personal name <persName xml:lang="sga">Dubáed</persName> might mean akin to 'having dark fire' (Broderick 2021, 10). MAQI is a form of MAQQI, later Old Irish <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/31166">macc</ref></foreign> meaning 'son'. DROATA is possibly Old Irish <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/18911">drúth</ref></foreign> meaning 'professional jester'.</p>
            </div>
